      <h2>Safety</h2>

      <div class="danger">
        <strong>Read this entire manual before assembly or use.</strong> Failure to follow safety instructions can result in serious injury.
      </div>

      <h3>General Safety</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Some dust created by power sanding contains chemicals known to cause cancer, birth defects, or other reproductive harm. Work in a well-ventilated area with approved safety equipment such as dust masks designed to filter microscopic particles.</li>
        <li>Read the entire owner&rsquo;s manual. Learn how to use the tool for its intended applications.</li>
        <li>Ground all tools. The 3-prong plug must be plugged into a 3-contact grounded receptacle. Do not remove the 3rd prong.</li>
        <li>Avoid a dangerous working environment. Do not use electrical tools in damp conditions or expose them to rain.</li>
        <li>Do not use electrical tools in the presence of flammable liquids or gases.</li>
        <li>Keep the work area clean, well lit, and organized. Avoid slippery floor surfaces.</li>
        <li>Keep visitors and children away from the immediate work area.</li>
        <li>Do not force the tool to perform operations it was not designed for.</li>
        <li>Wear proper clothing. No loose clothing, gloves, neckties, or jewelry. Use protective hair covering if hair is long.</li>
        <li>Childproof the workshop by removing switch keys, unplugging tools, and using padlocks.</li>
        <li>Always unplug the tool when making adjustments, changing parts, or performing maintenance.</li>
        <li>Keep protective guards in place and in working order.</li>
        <li>Avoid accidental starting. Ensure the power switch is OFF before plugging in.</li>
        <li>Remove all maintenance tools from the area before turning the machine on.</li>
        <li>Use only recommended accessories.</li>
        <li>Never leave a running tool unattended. Turn power off and wait for a complete stop.</li>
        <li>Do not stand on the tool.</li>
        <li>Maintain your balance. Wear oil-resistant rubber-soled shoes.</li>
        <li>Maintain tools with care. Keep abrasives in good condition and replace when worn.</li>
        <li>Check for damaged parts prior to each use.</li>
        <li>Do not operate while tired or under the influence of drugs, medication, or alcohol.</li>
        <li>Secure all work with clamps or jigs rather than holding by hand.</li>
        <li>Stay alert and use common sense when operating power tools.</li>
        <li>Always wear a dust mask. Direct particles away from face and body. Use dust collection wherever possible.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Sander-Specific Safety</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Do not operate until you have read all instructions.</li>
        <li>Do not attempt to operate until the machine is completely assembled.</li>
        <li>Do not turn on if any pieces are damaged or missing.</li>
        <li>The machine must be properly grounded.</li>
        <li>If unfamiliar with operation, obtain assistance from a qualified person.</li>
        <li>Firmly mount the machine to a flat, secure work surface or stand.</li>
        <li>Always wear protective eyewear.</li>
        <li>Always wear a dust mask and use adequate dust collection and ventilation.</li>
        <li>Do not wear loose clothing or jewelry. Keep long hair tied back.</li>
        <li>Make sure the power switch is OFF before plugging in.</li>
        <li>Make sure the power switch is OFF during assembly or setup.</li>
        <li>Make sure all safety guards and hardware are secure before operating.</li>
        <li>Use only recommended accessories and attachments.</li>
        <li>Use only manufacturer-recommended belt and disc sizes.</li>
        <li>Replace worn, frayed, or torn abrasives immediately.</li>
        <li>Keep face and hands clear of moving parts (belts, discs, pulleys).</li>
        <li>Keep power cords free of moving parts.</li>
        <li>Maintain a gap clearance of 1/16&quot; or less between the sanding surface and its table.</li>
        <li>Always support the workpiece with the table or backstop during sanding.</li>
        <li>Feed work into the rotating belt or disc on the downward direction so abrasive action pushes work onto the table.</li>
        <li>Do not force work into abrasives; burning or stalling may result.</li>
        <li>Remove debris from the work area. Keep the area neat and clean.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Electrical Safety</h3>
      <p>This tool must be grounded while in use to protect the operator from electric shock. It is equipped with a 3-prong grounding plug that must be plugged into a matching, properly grounded receptacle installed per local codes. Do not modify the plug.</p>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>Extension cords are not recommended.</strong> Plug the machine directly into a dedicated, grounded outlet. If an extension cord must be used, keep it as short as possible with a minimum gauge of 14 AWG. Only use 3-wire cords with a 3-prong grounding plug. Replace damaged cords immediately.
      </div>

