      <h3>Moving &amp; Installing the Sander</h3>
      <div class="warning">
        When moving the sander, lift with your hands positioned under the motor ends or belt and disc housings. <strong>Do not carry or move it using the attached work tables.</strong>
      </div>
      <p>The machine should be firmly bolted to a stand or solid, level workbench using the mounting holes in the base. For portability, bolt the sander permanently to a piece of plywood, then clamp the plywood to your workbench.</p>

      <h3>Mounting to a Workbench</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Position the sander on the workbench.</li>
        <li>Mark the workbench through the two mounting holes in the left and right sides of the base.</li>
        <li>Drill holes at the marks.</li>
        <li>Secure the sander using long bolts, washers, lock-washers, and nuts (or lag bolts; fasteners not supplied).</li>
      </ol>
      <img src="/workshop/manuals/rikon-50-161vs/p09_00.jpg" alt="Mounting sander to workbench with bolts" />

      <h3>Dust Chute Installation (Disc Sander)</h3>
      <p>If not pre-assembled, fasten the sanding disc dust chute and cover to the machine using the four Phillips M4 screws and washers.</p>
      <img src="/workshop/manuals/rikon-50-161vs/p09_02.jpg" alt="Disc sander dust chute installation" />

      <h3>Assembling the Belt Sander Table</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Locate the round-shaped belt-sanding table.</li>
        <li>Position the table by threading the belt and plate through the table&rsquo;s slot and square opening.</li>
        <li>Fasten the table to the frame using the table-adjustment knob and 8mm washer.</li>
        <li>Bring the adjustment knob&rsquo;s screw through the slot in the bracket on the underside of the table, then into the threaded hole in the frame.</li>
        <li>Tighten the handle to secure.</li>
      </ol>
      <img src="/workshop/manuals/rikon-50-161vs/p09_03.jpg" alt="Belt sander table assembly" />

      <h3>Assembling the Sanding Disc Table</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Tip the table up and slide the two small nipples from the rectangular mouth onto the two &lsquo;L&rsquo; mounting slots in the disc sander guide frame.</li>
        <li>Align the screw holes with the arched slots above the angle gauges.</li>
        <li>Fasten the table using the disc-table adjustment handles.</li>
        <li>The miter gauge slides into the slot on the disc-sanding table for small parts or angled sanding.</li>
      </ol>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/rikon-50-161vs/p10_00.jpg" alt="Disc table assembly — L-slot mounting" />
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/rikon-50-161vs/p10_01.jpg" alt="Disc table assembly — adjustment handles" />
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/rikon-50-161vs/p10_02.jpg" alt="Disc table assembly — completed" />
      </div>

      <h2>Belt Changes</h2>

      <h3>Belt Removal</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Remove the top lock-knob, clear plastic belt guard, and three Phillips screws that secure the side cover to the frame.</li>
        <li>Remove the side cover.</li>
        <li>Loosen the rear tracking knob to release belt tension. The spring-loaded tracking knob assembly can be pulled forward to assist in removing the belt over the rear idler wheel.</li>
        <li>Remove the belt from the three wheels.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Belt Installation</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Install the new belt around the top wheel, the large drive wheel, and then the rear idler wheel.</li>
        <li>Replace the side cover and reinstall the 3 Phillips screws, clear top guard, and lock-knob.</li>
        <li>Before using, check the belt tracking and adjust as necessary.</li>
      </ol>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/rikon-50-161vs/p12_00.jpg" alt="Belt removal — side cover removed showing three wheels" />
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/rikon-50-161vs/p12_01.jpg" alt="Belt installation — tracking knob and platen" />
      </div>

      <h3>Belt Sander Platen</h3>
      <p>The platen is a heavy steel support plate positioned behind the sanding belt, rising from the table level to several inches above the table surface. It supports the belt during sanding. Adjust the platen so it almost touches the back of the belt by loosening the two hex screws at the bottom of the platen.</p>
      <p>To remove the platen for curved-surface sanding, stropping, polishing, or other special operations, remove the two fastening screws and lift the platen out.</p>

      <h2>Disc Changes</h2>

      <div class="note">
        <strong>Hook &amp; loop sanding discs cannot be used with this sander.</strong> Only 6&quot; sanding discs with pressure-sensitive adhesive (PSA) backing are compatible.
      </div>

      <h3>Disc Changing with the Table in Place</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Angle the disc table down to reveal more of the sanding disc.</li>
        <li>Peel the used abrasive disc from the metal disc plate. A putty knife and hair dryer may help.</li>
        <li>Clean the disc plate of any residue. Mineral spirits will soften PSA adhesives. Rotate the disc by hand to access all surfaces.</li>
        <li>Peel the protective backing from the new PSA disc, center it, and press firmly onto the disc plate.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Disc Changing with the Table Removed</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Remove and set aside the miter gauge.</li>
        <li>Remove the 2 disc-table adjustment handles and washers.</li>
        <li>Tip the table up and remove it from the guard frame by slipping it back out of the slots.</li>
        <li>Peel the used disc and clean the plate as above.</li>
        <li>Center and press the new PSA sanding disc firmly onto the disc plate.</li>
        <li>Reinstall the table and handles.</li>
      </ol>
      <div class="image-row">
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/rikon-50-161vs/p11_00.jpg" alt="Disc table angle adjustment for disc access" />
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/rikon-50-161vs/p11_01.jpg" alt="Disc table angle gauge and lock knob" />
        <img src="/workshop/manuals/rikon-50-161vs/p11_02.jpg" alt="Removing used PSA disc with putty knife" />
      </div>

      <h2>Tracking Adjustment</h2>
      <p>The belt-tracking adjustment is factory-set so the belt runs true on the pulleys. If the belt tracks to one side, adjust the tracking knob on the back of the machine.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Clockwise:</strong> Belt tracks to the right, toward the sander&rsquo;s frame.</li>
        <li><strong>Counterclockwise:</strong> Belt tracks to the left, toward the side guard.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Belt Table Adjustments</h3>
      <p>For most operations the table remains at 90&deg; to the belt. A positive stop ensures fast 90&deg; positioning.</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Loosen the table-locking lever.</li>
        <li>Tilt the table back to the rear as far as possible.</li>
        <li>Using a square or protractor, check the angle against the platen. Adjust the rear adjustment screw as needed and lock with the hex nut.</li>
        <li>For other angles, tilt the table forward to the desired angle and tighten the locking lever.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Disc Table Adjustments</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Check the 90&deg; angle by placing a square on the table against the sanding disc.</li>
        <li>Loosen the 2 disc-table adjustment handles and set to 90&deg;.</li>
        <li>Retighten the handles.</li>
        <li>For other angles, loosen the handles, set the desired angle using the indicator, and retighten.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Operation</h2>

      <div class="danger">
        <strong>Never start the machine with work in contact with the sanding belt or disc.</strong> Sudden kickback can cause damage or injury.
      </div>

      <h3>Starting &amp; Speed Control</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Ensure the power switch is OFF and the variable speed switch is turned fully counterclockwise to its slowest setting.</li>
        <li>Stand to the side of the sander and plug in the power cord.</li>
        <li>Remaining to the side, turn the power switch to ON.</li>
        <li>Allow the sander to reach a steady speed for at least one minute, then increase RPM with the variable speed switch as needed.</li>
        <li>Place the workpiece flat on the appropriate table. Hold firmly to avoid chattering.</li>
        <li>When turning off, also return the variable speed dial to its slowest setting.</li>
        <li>Unplug the sander from the power source.</li>
      </ol>
      <img src="/workshop/manuals/rikon-50-161vs/p13_00.jpg" alt="ON/OFF switch and variable speed control" />

      <div class="note">
        <strong>Lockout feature:</strong> The power switch has a removable locking key. With the switch OFF, pull the key out to prevent unauthorized use. Reinsert the key to resume operations.
      </div>

      <h3>Miter Gauge</h3>
      <p>The miter gauge slides in the disc table slot and can be set up to 45&deg; right or left by loosening the lock-knob, setting the angle, and retightening.</p>
      <img src="/workshop/manuals/rikon-50-161vs/p13_02.jpg" alt="Miter gauge in disc table slot" />

      <h3>Dust Collection</h3>
      <p>The sander has two dust ports: one for the belt system and one for the disc system. Connect your dust collector to the appropriate port for the sanding mode in use. A 1-1/2&quot; OD / 1-1/4&quot; ID nozzle adapter is included for smaller-diameter hoses.</p>
      <img src="/workshop/manuals/rikon-50-161vs/p13_01.jpg" alt="Dust ports and nozzle adapter" />

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>Use a dust collection system.</strong> A mask or respirator is still recommended even when dust collection is in use.
      </div>

