      <h2>Troubleshooting</h2>

      <h3>Motor Will Not Start</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Low voltage &mdash; check power source for proper voltage.</li>
        <li>Open circuit or loose connections in motor &mdash; inspect all lead connections (send for servicing).</li>
        <li>Blown fuse or tripped breaker &mdash; check for short circuit or improper circuit match.</li>
        <li>Low temperature &mdash; start motor at high speed.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Motor Will Not Start &mdash; Fuses/Breakers Tripping</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Inspect cord and plug for damaged insulation and shorted wires.</li>
        <li>Inspect motor connections for loose or shorted terminals and worn insulation.</li>
        <li>Install correct fuses/breakers or switch to an appropriately sized circuit.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Motor Overheats</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Reduce load on motor (reduce pressure on the workpiece).</li>
        <li>Use a shorter, heavier-gauge extension cord or plug directly into an outlet.</li>
        <li>Improve air circulation around the motor; reduce run time to 30 minutes.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="warning">
        <strong>Do not touch hot motors.</strong> Class B motors run up to 95&deg;C (203&deg;F).
      </div>

      <h3>Motor Stalls or Runs Slow</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Reduce load on motor.</li>
        <li>Inspect connections for loose or shorted terminals.</li>
        <li>Correct low-voltage conditions (improper extension cord length/gauge).</li>
        <li>Install correct fuses or breakers.</li>
        <li>Replace motor capacitor if failed.</li>
        <li>Decrease belt tension if too tight.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Machine Slows During Operation</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Reduce feed rate.</li>
        <li>Ensure circuit wires or extension cords are proper gauge, or eliminate extension cords.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Excessive Vibration or Noise</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Tighten all fasteners.</li>
        <li>Adjust belt tension/tracking per instructions.</li>
        <li>Replace a weak or broken belt tension spring (service technician).</li>
        <li>Have a service technician adjust a loose idler roller.</li>
        <li>Replace a broken or defective sanding belt or disc.</li>
        <li>Decrease drive belt tension if too tight.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Burn Marks on Workpiece</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Use a coarser-grit sandpaper.</li>
        <li>Reduce pressure on workpiece while sanding.</li>
        <li>Do not hold the workpiece in one place for too long.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Deep Sanding Grooves or Scars</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Use a finer-grit belt or disc.</li>
        <li>Sand with the grain of the wood.</li>
        <li>Reduce pressure on the workpiece.</li>
        <li>Keep the workpiece moving while sanding.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Sanding Surface Clogs Quickly</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Reduce pressure on the workpiece.</li>
        <li>Softwood and resinous woods clog more quickly &mdash; clean or replace belts and discs more frequently.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Workpiece Lifts from Disc Table</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Sand on the left side of the sanding disc, where the disc rotates downward toward the table.</li>
      </ul>

